{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580382/1945082401/0993.xml":{"full_text":"f.\u00bb\nPage Fcrar\n\u25a01\nTOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nOfficial Publication\nToledo Industrial Union Council\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nPabii^hcd even Friday by Local No, 12\nLAW -UIO./425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nItTcmber\nof American Labor u\nEditor\nMa naming Editor\nAdvertising Manager\n.Melvin Schults\nO. J. Pecord\nBnruy Zawodny\nBoard of Trustees\nMelvin Schultz, Thomas Burke,\nRandolph Gray\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nUno year, bv mail, in advance.... ...1.50\nEntered at the Toledo. Ohio, post office as\nsecond class matter under tbs a*t ol\nAug. 24, 1912.\nRapid Reconversion\nIt is now apparent that the answer to\nfhe pressing unemployment problem with\nwhich we are faced consists in rapidly re\nconverting to civilian production and\ncreating full employment.\nActual reconversion does not seem to\npresent any unusual problems in view of\nthe fact that many industries have been\nletooling for several months. The task of\nmoving out government owned ma\nchinery used for war production and\ntnoving in the machines for normal pro\nduction is a relative simple matter.\nThe real test for the reconversion pro\ngram is going to come in the elimina\ntion of material bottlenecks, real or ar\ntificial. How quickly employment will\ntipswing is going to depend upon the\nspeed with which materials can be placed\nin the hands of the manufacturers. Thus,\nit will be seen that one of the most im\nportant steps in the entire reconversion\nand full employment program will be to\nproject industries from any combinations\nwhich might prevent them from getting\nthe materials necessary for their opera\ntion.\nOf equal importance, but impossible\nof realization until reconversion has oc\nfured, is a full employment program im\nplemented by legislation which will as\nsure the employment of every available\nworker in this country.\nWe definitely do not subscribe to the\ntheory that it is necssary to carry a \u201cnor\nmal float\u201d of unemployed at all times.\nOur war experience has taught us the\nfallacy of expecting to go from a mass of\nlinskilled, unprepared, unemployed work\ners to full production in a short time.\nThe fact that we were able to accomp\nlish the great production record of the\nwar is no indication that we could do it\n\u2022gain .should another emergency re\nquire our allout efforts.\nLabor, management and industry\nshould now direct their attention to\nSpeeding (ip the changes necessary to re\nsume full scale production and backing\nthe legislation to insure jobs for all.\nKenneth Cole\nEvery man who lives carves out his\nOwn memorial by the manner in which he\nlives and the service which he renders\npnto his fellowmen.\nIn such a vein we pause to pay sin\ncere tribute to Kenneth Cole, whom death\nhas removed from our midst at a time\nWhen his services are sorely needed.\nwill miss him.\nNo praise however eloquent can add\nto the stature of this good man whose life\nhas enriched all who knew him. He has\nleft an indelible imprint on the minds\nand hearts of many.\nAs first executive secretary of the To\nledo Industrial Council, Kenneth Cole\nheld office during crucial years. By his\ntireless efforts, his honesty, integrity and\nability he gave the citizens of Toledo a\nDew and truer picture of the ideals and\nobjectives of the CIO.\nOf a kind and gentle nature, Kenny\nCole took a deep interest in the Old News\nboys Goodfellow Association which he\nserved until taking up his duties in Wash\nington. Through his efforts, the annual\npaper sale for the Association has been\nheld with marked success for several\nyears in ail CIO shops.\nThe same qualities of heart and mind\nwhich endeared him to thousands of his\nfellow CIO members won him a whole\nhost of friends in Washington during the\ntime he served his Union in that city. A\nnewspaper editor of Washington wrote,\n\u201cmore people than you may he aware of\nare going to miss Ken Cole here.\u201d\nAnd so as we bid farewell to Kenneth\nCole, we can only say that we have been\nenriched by his life and the service which\nhe rendered to his union and fellow\nmembers of the CIO and realize that his\ngoing is our loss. Farewell to a good and\nfaihful servant of the workers.\n\u201cThe contemporary American Press is a\ntravesty of what a newspaper should be, leav\ning to one side all considerations of political\nand social philosophies. The populace more or\nless aware of this, takes its political guidance\nfrom other quarters\u2014from trade union papers,\nspecial form journals, religious organs, mag\nazines, books, newsletters and political leaders\ndirect\"\n\u2014Ferdinand Lundberg, Author.\nv\nIgnorance Is the school of race prejudice,\nand provincialism is its tutor. Its memory is\nstuffed with lies and its mind is warped by\nemotionalism. Pride is its book and snobbery\nis its pen. All the hatreds and fears, all the\ncruelties and prejudices of childhood are per\npetuated by it. It blinds the intellect and it\nhardens the heart. Its wisdor is wonderful\n\u2022nd fearful, for it never learns what is true,\n\u2022nd it never forgets what is false.\nClaude H. Heithus.\nWhat\u2019s\nNew?\nBy\nEdward Duck\nWith The\n45th Injantry\nms\nGertnany\nMARMOULON, France,\nAugust 9\u2014Things are happen\ning fast right now. The great\nest scientific discovery of mod\nern history is being unleashed\non the Japanese in order to\nend the war immediately, if\npossible. There is a rumor\nhere this morning that Russia\nhas declared war on Japan.\nAnd of course, everyone is\nstill talking about the British\nelection results.\nWhen one considers that\nthe energy released by one\npound of uranium would be\nsufficient to rase the Empire\nState Building twenty miles in\nthe air, it is not too difficult\nto believe that the war could\nend within a matter of hours.\nIf Russia has decided to\njump into the melee that, too,\nshould tend to cause the Jasp\nto decide that it is high time\nthat they call it quits.\nPOSTWAR\nThis leads us to the subject\nof \u201cpostwar\". Ladies and\ngentlemen, the long awaited\nday tnight well have arrived\nbefore this column goes to\npress. As it has been pre\ndicted, America is not ready\nfor it. No one should need\nto be told this.\nTemporary unemployment\nis the lesser of two evils, if\none wishes to choose between\nit and war. But this is not the\nsolution. Adequate unemploy\nment compensation and estab\nlished machinery for govern\nmental projects at decent wage\nlevels would have been the\nanswer. It could have been\ndone.\nProvidence smiled upon\nGreat Britain and gave the\ncommon people relief from\nconservative Toryism. Too\nmany people don\u2019t know the\ntruth about the British elec\ntion and the reasons for the\n\u201cswing to the left\u2019\u2019. If it took\na vigilante group to move\nyour sick wife and baby into\na house of some kind while\nhouses were vacant you would\nwant a change, too! The\npeople wanted a new deal and\nthey finally got it. Promises\nalone do not provide food or\nshelter for cold and hungry\nmillions. Britain\u2019s postwar\nfuture looks bright, indeed,\nnotwithstanding the poisonous\nremarks of certain self\nfl pointed American spokes\nmen.\nIMPERIALISM\nIf Hitler were alive\u2014or if\nhe is alive\u2014it is now diffi\ncult for him or anyone else\nto shout about British \u201cim\nperialism.\u201d The policies of the\nincoming government will\nbear this out. The contempt\nwhich many have had for the\nBritish nation, because of ccr\nlain things which I had best\nnot discuss until I am out of\nuniform, is vanishing.\nIn the British election lhe\nissues were clearly defined.\nOne party stood for one thing,\nthe other party for something\nelse. Campaign speeches were\nbitter, and the contestants\nshowed each other little\nmercy. They were not hypo\ncrites.\nThere is nothing \u201cdanger\nous\u2019\u2019 about the Labor victory\nin Great Britain. Selfish in\nterests, in Britain, America,\nand elsewhere, feel them\nselves slipping, and fear for\ntheir financial and political\nfuture. They see the hand\nwriting on the wall.\nPERMANENT PEACE\nSo on the one hand we have\na scientific discovery which\nby its very immensity in\npower of destruction makes\nfuture war prohibited, while\non the other hand develop\nments of worldwide political\nsignificance enhance the pros\npect of permanent peace for\nall countries of the world.\nThe atom bomb Is so terrible\nthat it could very possibly\nbring about the ruin of the\nworld if it became an instru\nment for the waging of world\nwar in years to come.\nTherefore, it remains for\nall rations to seek other\nmeans of settling disputes\nhereafter. Great Brttain\u2019i\nchange for the better makes\npossible the establishment ol\nreal cooperation between the\ngreat powers of the world,\nand removes the bad taste\ncaused by too many years of\nsomething the people didn\u2019t\nlike but couldn\u2019t whip.\nWe have a few problems\nourselves. We don\u2019t have tn\nsolve our problems in the\nsame manner that Great Bri\ntain did, bue we do have to\nsolve them. In \"Britain the\npeople did it. In America the\npeople will have to do it.\nYou are the people. The time\nU now!\nUh\nIW\na'??-\nIt\u2019s News\nTo Me..\nBy O. 7. Pecord\nWOTTA BOMB\nNews of the atomic bomb which apparently brought abou\nthe desire for surrender on the part of the Japs, poses a lot\nof questions that the philosophers, theologians, scientists and\nstatesmen of the world will be kicking around, for quite some\ntime.\nSome theologians have come forth with the arguments pro\nand con regarding the morality of dropping atomic blastings\nupon whole populations \u201cin a just war.\" This presupposes that\nthere can be a just war so let\u2019s skip the theologians.\nScientists tell us of the possibilities of using atomic power\nto supplant coal, oil and gasoline as motivating forces. We are\ntreated to some idea of the power of the atomic explosion by\nbeing told that an atomic charge the size of an early June pea\nwould drive an ocean liner across the sea and back again and\nthat it is possible to circumvent the globe in a plane with a\ncharge the size of a brick.\nAS A WEAPON\nBut the whole atomic business seems to be.more interesting\nto the people of the world when viewed in its destructive power\nto blast people out of their desire to wage war, and that is where\nthe catch comes in.\nIf American scientists could discover ways of loosening the\ndynamic power of the atom, what is there to prevent the scien\ntific men of other nations from accomplishing the same results\nand perhaps better? Obviously there is no monopoly on brains\nor scientific research. What we have done could and probably\nwill be done by those who do not yet share our secret.\nIn the hands of the wrong people, and there are always\nwrong people as we realized during and after the late unpleas\nantness in Europe, the Pacific, China and the rest of the world,\natomic power could become a force for evil the like of which\nthe world has never before witnessed.\nNow that we know the terrific power contained with the\natom by three demonstrations, what is there to prevent some\nother nation from developing this power and loosening it upon\nOther nations without warning?\nIf the atomic bomb could be developed where it could be\ndropped from a plane and destroy practically an entire city,\nWhat is there to stop further development to the point where\nan atomic bomb could be shot through the stratosphere and\nmade to land in Monroe, Michigan destroying both Toledo and\nDetroit at the same time? Jules Verne was a piker when com\npared to the possibilities that can be devised for the future of\nthe atom. No doubt, we are on the verge of the atomic age.\nWHAT RESULTS?\nWhat the results of the development of atomic power will\nbe is entirely dependent upon the amount of scientific research\nwork which is put into this newly developed source of energy.\nOne thing is certain, it will not eliminate the need for a working\nclass unless by some unfortuate event, the entire human race\nbe eleiminated by the thing it discovered but could not control.\nThe atomic bomb may bring about revolutionary changes\nin our manufacturing processes and chanfee our habits and ways\nof thinking, but people will still need to eat, clothe themselves,\nlive in houses and use whatever gadgets are available for light\nening their work. It will not establish Utopia.\nAnd as we contemplate all the wonderful possibilities con\ntained in the newly revealed power and the significance of what\nhas already been accomplished for death and destruction, we\n\u2022re struck with one thought\u2014what will happen to workers in\ntheir disputes with employers? Will the atomic bomb be used\non them?\nNo matter how much tear gas, guns, clubs, fists and other\nImplements have been used in the past to subdue the workers,\nWe can be certain of one thing. The atomic bomb will definitely\nnot be used to break strikes. Remember ,Uie bosses still need\nyou.\nUNIONISM\nBy RUTH TAYLOR\nUnionism Is a road, not a\ndestination. It is a way, not\nin end. Like a road, union\nism has its ups and downs, its\nhills and valleys, its bypaths,\nits detours.\nUnionism is something in\ncomprehensible to those who\ndo not know Democracy.\nThey cannot imagine a road\nConforming to the contour of\nthe land their highways\nmust smash through in ge\nometric lines. They cannot\nimagine a way of life that con\nforms itself to and serves the\npeople who compose it. Their\nway of life must smash\nthrough the lives of subjects\ncompressing them ruthlessly\nto one set pattern. The great\nest handicap of tyrants is their\nlack of imagination, their lack\nof the realization that a man\nWill do more because he wants\nto, than he will because he is\ntold to.\nUnionism gains its strength\nfrom voluntary cooperation\u2014a\nunity of purpose and action. It\ndoes not demand ol its follow-\nv-f I\nTHE TOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\ni\nSOOMritt Torever! ix\nrrs that they must all thfnl\nalike, any more than that all\nroads must be alike. It does\nhowever call for a spirit of\ncohesion on all fundamental\nprinciples. To be a vital force\nunionism must be based upon\nmutual understanding and\nmust be motivated by mutual\nideals, or principles.\nThe principles of trade\nunionism are the same as those\nof democracy\u2014the right of\nfree men to organize, to as\nsociate with their fellow men\nin action for the common\ngood, to speak freely and\nwithout fear, and to act ac\ncording to fheir own con\nscience.\nThe greatest protection\nagainst totalitarianism, wheth\ner of the left or the right, is a\nstrong, organized, self-disci\nplined labor unionism dedi\ncated to a high purpose. Self\ndiscipline is what differenti\nates free labor from the\nforced labor of dictator-ruled\nstates.\nt.\nSAW i\n\"F .-i\nX- i:\n7.\n\u2022rom AMMUNITION, UAW-CIO\nWashington\nLaborRcport\nBy Bradford V. Carter\nLPA Columnist\nCONFUSION TO CHAOS\nFrom confusion to chaos is\nthe best way to describe the\neffect of the sudden ending\nof the Pacific War on postwar\nplans. Before the abrupt end\ning of hostilities it was\nthought that time would per\nmit Washington to muddle\nthrough with some kind Of\nminimum program. Now the\nbottom has suddenly dropped\nout and revealed for every\nbody to see\u2014our homefront\nPearl Harbor.\nSynthetic optimism is the\nkeynote sounded most fre\nquently in Washington now.\nTopside Washington officials\ngreet one another with a\nsickly grin and mutter some\nthing like \u201cthe natural resili\nence of the economy will take\ncare of everything. Oh, yes,\nwe may have something like\n8 million unemployed by\nspring but it will be only tem\nporary.\"\nThe blunt truth of the mat\nter is that, as labor people\nhave been saying until they\nwere blue in the face, eco\nnomicially we are completely\nunprepared for the problems\nraised by the end of the war.\nKEY FIGURES\nListen to some of the key\nfigures in the situation:\n1. As of April 1945 there\nwere more than 12 million\nmen and women in the armed\nforces. Seven million at least\nare to be demobilized within\nthe next year.\n2. As of the end of June\n1945, there wcro 8 million\nworkers engaged, in direct\nmunitions production, to say\nnothing of workers engaged\nin supporting activities which\nthis figure does not include.\nPlans call for the immediate\ncutback of more'than 90% of\ntotal procurement.\n3. The official estimates\npredict unemployment of more\nthan 5 millions by the end of\nthe year and 8 million by\nspring of 1946.\n4. What nobody has said\npublicly so far is that, under\nthe most favoraole conditions,\nour economy has never been\nable to increase employment\nby more than 3 millions per\nyear\u2014and that unemployment\nhas mver been reduced by\nmore than 2\u2019j millions per.\nyear. In the absence of her\nculean efforts, this means that\nit will take several years be\nfore the unemployed are ab\nsorbed\u2014assuming the capacity\nof industry to accomplish this,\n5. In 1940 there were about\n50 million people working. In\n1945 there are something short\nof 64 millions working and in\nthe armed forces. Allowing\nfor the maximum withdrawal\nof workers from the labor\nmarket after complete demo\nbilization of the armed forces,'\nwe shall still need to find jobs\nfor 13 to 15 million more\nworkers than were employed\nin 1940, our la^t peacetime\nyear.\nAU of these facts clearly\npoint to a situation in 1945\nand 1946 which will not be\nmet by \"a return to normalcy\u2019\u2019\n\u201cand letting things take their\ncourse.\" A return to normalcy\nspells i s a s e r\u2014unless we\ncatch on right quickly that\ngovernment will have to exer\ncise a positive role in finding\njobs for every one who wants\nto work.\n-\u25a0\u2014n11,11 -i-- v- _______\ni\nOn The\nBeam\nBy\nClayton\nFountain\n\u25a03^\no\n..i\n3\nx.\nIk-1\nWhere do we go from here?\nThere should be no need to\nask this question. It has been\nanswered a million times or\nSnore already. It was an\nswered in the Atlantic Char\nter, and in all the other formal\ndeclarations of war aims is\nsued by the leaders of the\nVnited Nations.\nThe answer was given on\nthe occasion of tvery War\nBond drive, every appeal for\nblood donors, every demand\nfor increased war production.\nThe answer was always the\nSame:\n\u201cWe have to win this war\nin order to save democracy\nand to set the world on the\npath to universal liberty, se\ncurity, abundance and broth\nerhood.\"\nThese were the words, the\nslogans, the declarations of\nIntent with which we were\nencouraged to give our all to\nthe war effort.\nTHE PAY-OFF\nOkay, we came through.\nWe have won the military\nphase of the war against\nFascism\u2014now it is time for\nthe pay-off. It is time to give\nwith the \u201cliberty, security,\nabundance and brotherhood.\u201d\nIn England, the pay-off\nseems to be proceeding on\nschedule. The British people\n\u00bbre serious about stepping\nforward to claim the better\nworld for which they were\ntold this war was being\nfought. They have elected a\nnew Labor government and\ncommanded it to enact legis\nlation that will transform\n\u201cliberty, security, abundance\nand brotherhood\" from phras\nes into tangible realities.\nThey are going to collect\ntheir war aims in the form of\nhousing, jobs, higher wages,\nguaranteed medical care and\nsocial ownership of monopo\nlistic industries. The device\nof social ownership will re\nduce profits, dividends, in\nterest and other forms of un\nearned income, and so divert\na swelling flood of purchasing\npower into the hands of the\ncommon people.\nWHAT ABOUT AMERICA?\nBut, while we cheer the\ncourage and intelligence with\nwhich our British brothers\nare implementing the pay\noff of their war aims, we must\nthink about the practical prob\nlem of claiming our own\nshare of the \u201cliberty, secur\nity, abundance and brother\nhood\u201d for which we fought\nthis war and won it.\nWhat about America?\nHow shall we implement\nthe pay-off of our war aims\nin this country?\nThere are those among us\nwho are shouting loudly that\nwe do not need to worry\nabout this question. They say\nthat all wc have to do is give\nprivate enterprise a free hand,\nand the corporations will of\ntheir own free will take us\ndown the high road to the\ngood life.\nIf ever we needed to look\na gift horse in the mouth, this\nis a time that demands such\na down-to-earth inspection of\nthe manner in which big busi\nness proposes to award us our\nshare of \u201cliberty, security,\nabundance and brotherhood.\"\nTHE VANDENBERG TRAP\nThe big business approach to\nto implementation of the pay\noff of our war aims is phoney\nand completely unrealistic. It\nis typified by Senator Arthur\nVandenberg\u2019s silly notion that\nlabor and capital can get to\ngether and plan to unite a\nround a common program.\nThis is an age of miracles,\nbut we have still not reached\nthe point where lions and\nlambs can lay down together.\nThe big-time industrialists,\nbankers and landlords in Ame\nrica are still going to grab for\nall the profits they can get. So\nlong as they do this, the com\nmon people will not have\nenough income to live de\ncently.\nLet us not fall into the\nVandenberg trap. The only\nway to get our just share of\n\u201cliberty, security, abundance\nand brotherhood\u201d is to build\nourselves a party like the\nBritish Labor Party, vote our\nselves into power tell the\nplutocrats to get the hell out\nof the way and take what\nis rightfully ours.\nRegional\nViews\nBy Richard (josser\nFriday, August 24, 194ST\nAlong with trying to get the unemployment\nbenefits increased effective this month instead\nof October, we are going to do everything in\nour power to speed the reconversion period\nand full employment for which we have been\nasking for many weeks. We believe that if the\ngovernment can speed the flow of materials\nto the plants of America that the reconversion\nperiod can be greatly shortened and that we\ncan again have full scale production of civilian\ngoods.\nOur imn^pdiate program is to insist that\nCongress increase unemployment benefits to\n$25 for 26 weeks and at the same time pass\nthe full employment bill which will give every\nworker in this country a job. Our most im\nportant objective from now on must be 60,\n000,000 jobs.\nFrom The Desk\nof\nMelvin Schultz\nPresident,\nLocal 12, UAW-CIO\nThe topic which I wish to take up at this\ntime is in regard to Veterans\u2019 Legislation,\ndealing with employment and labor matters.\nThe Selective Service Act which makea\nmen from 18 to 45 liable for service in th\u00bb\nArmed Forces also provides for reemployment',\nseniority and other rights for them upon dis\ncharge Trom service.\nA Veterans\u2019 Personnel Division within\nSelective Service to assist qualified Veterans\nin employment matters was established by the\nSelective Service Act.\nAt the present time, the functions of thr\nPersonnel Division are confined to assistance\nin obtaining reemployment. This Act requires\nFederal Government and all private employers\nto reinstate an employee leaving a job other\nthan a temporary one on condition that:\n1. He receives an honorable discharge. 9\n2. He is still qualified to perform the dutiei\nof the job.\n3. He makes application for reemployment\nwithin 90 days after he is discharged.\nUnless the employer\u2019s circumstances have\nso changed as to make it impossible or un\nreasonable to do so, the Veteran is to be rein\nstated to such position or to a position of like\nseniority, statuts, and pay.\nA returning Veteran, in order to claim\nreinstatement in a position which has been up\ngraded, must be qualified to perform the duties\nand functions of this new position. If he is un\nable to qualify for this upgraded job he is,\nnevertheless, entitled to a job similar in sen\niority, status, and pay to the one which he\nleft.\nA Veteran entitled to reemployment may\nnot be discharged from his job without cause\nwithin one year after he returns.\nThe law requires that the worker be re\ninstated without loss of seniority and shall b$.\nentitled to participate in insurance or other\nbenefits in effect with the employer at the time\nsuch person was inducted into the Armed\nForces.\nThis is interpreted to mean that a service\nman\u2019s seniority accumulates during his service\nto the same extent and in the same manner\nas if he had remained in continuous employ\nment.\nThese same rights apply also to women in\nthe Armed Services.\nOstrich-minded Congressmen and certain\nBusinessmen refuse to believe the postwar\nperiod poses any problems. Let them consider\nthe following dislocation of population during\nthe war: Puget Sound\u2014269.000 in-migrants\nPortland, Oregon\u2014220,000 in-migrants San\nFrancisco\u2014515,000 in-migrants: Los Angeles\n83,000 in-migrants San Diego\u2014165,000 in\nmigrants Hampton Roads, Virginia\u2014166,000\nin-migrants Detroit\u2014254,000 in-migrants and\nMobile, Alabama\u201484,000 in-migrants.\nI\n^hii****\ni-r w\nI\nfe\nIS\u00ab\n\u2019\u2019\u2022\u2019r Aw.,\nDirector Region 2B, UAW-CIO\nNEED FOR ACTION\nInstead of telling the workers \u201cwe told you Z\"\nso\u201d since government cancellation of millions\nof dollars worth of war contracts, caused the\nlayoff of thousands of Toledo workers, thq\nUnion must roll up its sleeves and pitch in and\nhelp the workers over the slack period.\nIn Toledo, the regional office and Local 12\nhave set up a new office on the 4th floor of\nLocal 12\u2019s headquarters for the assistance of\nthose unemployed. I advise everyone to visit\nthis office for information and advice before\nmaking application for their unemployment\ninsurance. By doing this, we may be able to\nsuggest ways and means to those out of jobs\nthat will be of great benefit to them.\nOur next step is to petition Governor Frank\nLausche to immediately call the Ohio state\nlegislature into session to write an emergency\nclause into the new unemployment compensa\ntion bill which will make it effective this\nmonth. If this is not done, the new bill in\ncreasing the benefits from $16 to $21 and from\n18 to 22 weeks will not become effective until\nthe middle of October.\nWRITE LETTERS\nIt would be of great aid to the unions who\nare seeking to get the Governor to move, if\nall the members, officers, and Units of all Lo\ncal Unions would write letters to Governor\nLausche, immediately. This is an emergency\nand failure to act now stamps us as being in\ndifferent to what happens.\nI happen to know that none of those who\nhave been laid off since last week are indif\nferent. I have yet to meet one of the people\nwho are out of job who do not want to get\nback to work at the earliest possible time. It\nwill be wise if these people would show their\ninterest and help us to help them by joining\nin our campaign to get the state legislature to\ndo something to give every unemployed person\nan additional five dollars a week. This is cer\ntainly worth while, and will become more so\nas the savings of the workers dwindle.\nRECONVERSION","height":"26955","width":"20637"}}
